<paragraph id="112B36F9FFCCFF95D6FFFB08FCAE2950" blockId="4.[140,887,1257,1285]" box="[140,887,1257,1285]" pageId="4" pageNumber="123">
<heading id="4A638195FFCCFF95D6FFFB08FCAE2950" box="[140,887,1257,1285]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="4" pageNumber="123" reason="3">
<taxonomicName id="D6944D7AFFCCFF95D6FFFB08FD8D2956" authority="(Gestro, 1877)" baseAuthorityName="Gestro" baseAuthorityYear="1877" box="[140,596,1257,1284]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Pseudocastalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arabica">
<emphasis id="23E0EAEBFFCCFF95D6FFFB08FD8D2956" bold="true" box="[140,596,1257,1284]" pageId="4" pageNumber="123">
<emphasis id="23E0EAEBFFCCFF95D6FFFB08FE442951" bold="true" box="[140,413,1257,1284]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="123">Pseudocastalia arabica</emphasis>
(Gestro, 1877)
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Subfamily: 
<taxonomicName id="D6944D7AFFCCFF95D496FB0BFCA92950" authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1857" box="[741,880,1258,1285]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Polycestinae">Polycestinae</taxonomicName>
)
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="112B36F9FFCCFF95D6FFFAD1FC0C2ADD" blockId="4.[140,1108,1328,1672]" pageId="4" pageNumber="123">
Bilý published a series of five papers describing the Saudi Arabian buprestid fauna (
<bibRefCitation id="75054B08FFCCFF95D257FAD1FF10293B" author="Bily S" pageId="4" pageNumber="123" pagination="215 - 222" refId="ref5098" refString="Bily S (1978) Insects of Saudi Arabia Coleoptera: family Buprestidae. Fauna of Saudi Arabia 1: 215 - 222." type="journal article" year="1978">Bilý 1978</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="75054B08FFCCFF95D6A5FAB5FECA293B" author="Bily S" box="[214,275,1364,1390]" pageId="4" pageNumber="123" pagination="119 - 121" refId="ref5122" refString="Bily S (1980) Insects of Saudi Arabia Coleoptera: family Buprestidae (Part 2). Fauna of Saudi Arabia 2: 119 - 121." type="journal article" year="1980">1980</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="75054B08FFCCFF95D76CFAB5FE85293B" author="Bily S" box="[287,348,1364,1390]" pageId="4" pageNumber="123" pagination="111 - 115" refId="ref5150" refString="Bily S (1982) Insects of Saudi Arabia Coleoptera: family Buprestidae (Part 3). Fauna of Saudi Arabia 4: 111 - 115." type="journal article" year="1982">1982</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="75054B08FFCCFF95D71AFAB2FE7F293B" author="Bily S" box="[361,422,1363,1390]" pageId="4" pageNumber="123" pagination="160 - 164" refId="ref5178" refString="Bily S (1985) Coleoptera: family Buprestidae of Saudi Arabia (Part 4). Fauna of Saudi Arabia 7: 160 - 164." type="journal article" year="1985">1985</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="75054B08FFCCFF95D7C0FAB5FE2B293B" author="Bily S" box="[435,498,1364,1390]" pageId="4" pageNumber="123" pagination="31 - 35" refId="ref5205" refString="Bily S (1990) Coleoptera: family Buprestidae of Saudi Arabia (Part 5). Fauna of Saudi Arabia 11: 31 - 35." type="journal article" year="1990">1990</bibRefCitation>
). In all, some 31 species of this family were listed and discussed, but one species despite its name was absent from the lists: 
<taxonomicName id="D6944D7AFFCCFF95D5C9FA96FF0529E1" baseAuthorityName="Gestro" baseAuthorityYear="1877" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Pseudocastalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arabica">
<emphasis id="23E0EAEBFFCCFF95D5C9FA96FF0529E1" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="123">Pseudocastalia arabica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This is a poorly known jewel beetle from a genus that contains about seven species of wood-boring beetles from Africa and Asia. In 2008, whilst examining beetles originally from the 
<collectingRegion id="D350F81BFFCCFF95D719FA01FE3029AF" box="[362,489,1504,1530]" country="United Arab Emirates" name="Abu Zaby" pageId="4" pageNumber="123">Abu Dhabi</collectingRegion>
ENHG Collection, the authors were surprised to find a total of 16 examples of this very dark sub-metallic green beetle (
<figureCitation id="89AF2A7CFFCCFF95D50EF9E2FC1B2A4B" box="[893,962,1539,1566]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="5.[140,212,1126,1148]" captionTargetBox="[255,881,165,1106]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[255,992,165,1106]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 2. The jewel beetle Pseudocastalia arabica. A jewel beetle from the JAAENHG Insect Collection; this specimen was originally collected by J. N. B. Brown in Abu Dhabi and kept in the ENHG Collection there (photograph by B. Howarth)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3767381" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3767381/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="123">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Even more surprising was the observation that all specimens had been correctly determined and labeled, something that was usually lacking even for common species in this collection. All had been collected in 
<collectingRegion id="D350F81BFFCCFF95D7D8F98CFDF32AD2" box="[427,554,1645,1671]" country="United Arab Emirates" name="Abu Zaby" pageId="4" pageNumber="123">Abu Dhabi</collectingRegion>
during 
<date id="652A1039FFCCFF95D4F7F98CFCC62AD2" box="[644,799,1645,1672]" pageId="4" pageNumber="123" value="1988" valueMax="1990">1988 to 1990</date>
by Bish Brown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="45EB6671FFCDFF94D6FFFB87FE0D28E9" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3767381" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3767381" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3767381/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" startId="5.[140,212,1126,1148]" targetBox="[255,881,165,1106]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph id="112B36F9FFCDFF94D6FFFB87FE0D28E9" blockId="5.[140,1108,1126,1212]" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">
<emphasis id="23E0EAEBFFCDFF94D6FFFB87FF372829" bold="true" box="[140,238,1126,1148]" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Figure 2.</emphasis>
The jewel beetle 
<emphasis id="23E0EAEBFFCDFF94D7FDFB87FD82282E" box="[398,603,1126,1147]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">
<taxonomicName id="D6944D7AFFCDFF94D7FDFB87FD8E282E" baseAuthorityName="Gestro" baseAuthorityYear="1877" box="[398,599,1126,1147]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Pseudocastalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arabica">Pseudocastalia arabica</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
A jewel beetle from the JAAENHG Insect Collection; this specimen was originally collected by J. N. B. Brown in Abu Dhabi and kept in the ENHG Collection there (photograph by B. Howarth).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection id="598E6572FFCDFF97D6CAFB0BFE792E84" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="125" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" type="description">
<paragraph id="112B36F9FFCDFF94D6CAFB0BFC0D29AF" blockId="5.[140,1108,1258,1672]" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">
Along with the 
<collectingRegion id="D350F81BFFCDFF94D718FB0BFE322951" box="[363,491,1258,1284]" country="United Arab Emirates" name="Abu Zaby" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Abu Dhabi</collectingRegion>
insect collection, the Al Ain ENHG had taken charge of some miscellaneous papers and letters that dealt with the collection itself. Amongst these was found a letter on NHM headed paper dated 
<date id="652A1039FFCDFF94D577FAD1FC2D291F" box="[772,1012,1327,1354]" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" value="1988-09-28">
28 
<superScript id="E6E19BB1FFCDFF94D552FACEFCF62968" attach="left" box="[801,815,1327,1341]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">th</superScript>
September 1988
</date>
and addressed to Bish Brown. It gave the identity of a specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="D6944D7AFFCDFF94D55CFAB2FBF92938" baseAuthorityName="Gestro" baseAuthorityYear="1877" box="[815,1056,1363,1389]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Pseudocastalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arabica">
<emphasis id="23E0EAEBFFCDFF94D55CFAB2FBF92938" box="[815,1056,1363,1389]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Pseudocastalia arabica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that Brown had sent to the museum, thanked him for the specimen and reminded him that a cash remittance was required to pay for the identification! Whether it was the expense of this exercise or because the collection did not contain any other species quite as obscure as 
<taxonomicName id="D6944D7AFFCDFF94D69AFA00FE8A29AF" baseAuthorityName="Gestro" baseAuthorityYear="1877" box="[233,339,1504,1530]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Pseudocastalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arabica">
<emphasis id="23E0EAEBFFCDFF94D69AFA00FE8A29AF" box="[233,339,1504,1530]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">P. arabica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is unknown, but no other such letters have been found.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="112B36F9FFCDFF97D6CAF9E2FE272D24" blockId="5.[140,1108,1258,1672]" lastBlockId="6.[140,1108,167,721]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="125" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">
Since MG’s son, Conrad, was employed by the NHM as curator of 
<taxonomicName id="D6944D7AFFCDFF94D5C9F9E2FBEE2A48" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[954,1079,1539,1565]" class="Magnoliopsida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="order">Coleoptera</taxonomicName>
at the time the specimens and letter were discovered, he was asked to look for Brown’s specimen in the NHM Collection. It could not be found, but the NHM did have 
<specimenCount id="0792FD70FFCDFF94D245F9ABFF262AD2" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" type="generic">36 specimens</specimenCount>
of this beetle, amongst them the 
<typeStatus id="CE2F885BFFCDFF94D4F6F98CFCC52AD2" box="[645,796,1645,1671]" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Paralectotype</typeStatus>
from 
<collectingRegion id="D350F81BFFCDFF94D517F98CFC7D2AD2" box="[868,932,1645,1671]" country="Yemen" name="'Adan" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Aden</collectingRegion>
. There were 18 other examples from present day 
<collectingCountry id="69837669FFCEFF97D78EFF46FD952C94" box="[509,588,167,193]" name="Yemen" pageId="6" pageNumber="125">Yemen</collectingCountry>
, three from present day 
<collectingCountry id="69837669FFCEFF97D52AFF46FC352C94" box="[857,1004,167,193]" name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="6" pageNumber="125">Saudi Arabia</collectingCountry>
, a couple from 
<collectingCountry id="69837669FFCEFF97D6BEFF2BFEF32CB1" box="[205,298,202,228]" name="Somalia" pageId="6" pageNumber="125">Somalia</collectingCountry>
, one from 
<collectingCountry id="69837669FFCEFF97D7DFFF2BFE3E2CB1" box="[428,487,202,228]" name="Syria" pageId="6" pageNumber="125">Syria</collectingCountry>
, five from 
<collectingCountry id="69837669FFCEFF97D414FF2BFD7B2CB1" box="[615,674,202,228]" name="India" pageId="6" pageNumber="125">India</collectingCountry>
and two from 
<collectingCountry id="69837669FFCEFF97D526FF2BFC452CB1" box="[853,924,202,228]" name="South Korea" pageId="6" pageNumber="125">Korea</collectingCountry>
. Five specimens were without data, but it is impossible to say if Brown’s Abu Dhabi example is amongst these. However, from this set of data, it is obvious that the Abu Dhabi material plugs a gap in the Afro-tropical – Oriental distribution of this species, as well as providing the first records from eastern Arabia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="112B36F9FFCEFF97D6CAFE9BFE792E84" blockId="6.[140,1108,167,721]" pageId="6" pageNumber="125">
Apparently very little is known about the biology of 
<taxonomicName id="D6944D7AFFCEFF97D574FE9BFC782DC1" authorityName="Kraatz" authorityYear="1896" box="[775,929,378,404]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Pseudocastalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="23E0EAEBFFCEFF97D574FE9BFC782DC1" box="[775,929,378,404]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="125">Pseudocastalia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, including 
<taxonomicName id="D6944D7AFFCEFF97D6C9FE7FFEFE2DE2" baseAuthorityName="Gestro" baseAuthorityYear="1877" box="[186,295,413,439]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Pseudocastalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arabica">
<emphasis id="23E0EAEBFFCEFF97D6C9FE7FFEFE2DE2" box="[186,295,413,439]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="125">P. arabica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, except that the larvae are borers of dead wood and some species are considered to be pests (
<bibRefCitation id="75054B08FFCEFF97D7EFFE21FD9E2D8F" author="Abivardi C" box="[412,583,448,474]" pageId="6" pageNumber="125" pagination="445 - 1033" refId="ref5030" refString="Abivardi C (2001) Iranian Entomology Vol. 2. Applied Entomology. Springer, New York, 445 - 1033 pp." type="book chapter" year="2001">Abivardi 2001</bibRefCitation>
: 
<bibRefCitation id="75054B08FFCEFF97D426FE21FC532D8F" author="Biosecurity Australia" box="[597,906,448,474]" pageId="6" pageNumber="125" refId="ref5232" refString="Biosecurity Australia (2002) Citrus Imports from the Arab Republic of Egypt. A review un- der existing import conditions for citrus from Israel. www. daff. gov. au / _ data / assets / word _ doc / 0014 / 24701 / fin _ egyptian _ citrus. doc." type="book" year="2002">
Biosecurity 
<collectingCountry id="69837669FFCEFF97D4AEFE21FC992D8F" box="[733,832,448,474]" name="Australia" pageId="6" pageNumber="125">Australia</collectingCountry>
2002
</bibRefCitation>
). Indeed, there is anecdotal evidence on the internet of the related species 
<taxonomicName id="D6944D7AFFCEFF97D577FE05FC582DA8" box="[772,897,484,509]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Pseudocastalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aegyptica">
<emphasis id="23E0EAEBFFCEFF97D577FE05FC582DA8" box="[772,897,484,509]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="125">P. aegyptica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a pest, infesting structural timbers in a building. There is an air of mystery surrounding the Abu Dhabi specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="D6944D7AFFCEFF97D758FDCAFE412E11" baseAuthorityName="Gestro" baseAuthorityYear="1877" box="[299,408,554,580]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Pseudocastalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arabica">
<emphasis id="23E0EAEBFFCEFF97D758FDCAFE412E11" box="[299,408,554,580]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="125">P. arabica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Why so many specimens from the same collection locality with no others known from eastern Arabia or since 
<quantity id="D66C9B1CFFCEFF97D4BDFDACFCFE2E32" box="[718,807,589,615]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0546" pageId="6" pageNumber="125" unit="in" value="1990.0">1990 in</quantity>
Abu Dhabi? Why was this species, but no others, sent off to the NHM for identification? Could the beetles have come from infested timbers in an Abu Dhabi building in the 1980’s? We will probably never know the answers.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
